{{otheruses|red-colored hot springs|various Akayu Onsen in Japan|赤湯温泉}} {{Notability|date=August 2011}} {{Citations needed|date=November 2011}} [[File:141108 Gekkoen Yugetsusanso Arima Onsen Kobe Japan04bs3.jpg|thumb|{{ill|Arima Onsen|ja|有馬温泉}} Kinsen]] [[File:Beppu Chinoike-jigoku01n4272.jpg|thumb|{{ill|Chinoike Jigoku|ja|血の池地獄}} at {{ill|Beppu Onsen|ja|柴石温泉}}]] '''Akayu''' (赤湯) is a general term for hot springs ({{ill|Onsen|ja|温泉}}) with red-colored water. It is a type of {{ill|Murky Hot Springs|ja|にごり湯}}.
== Overview == The term "Akayu" is often used to describe hot springs where the {{ill|Yunohana (mineral deposits)|ja|湯の花}}, which precipitate or settle in the bath, are red in color. This red hue is typically due to the high iron content in the hot spring water, which oxidizes to form iron oxide deposits. A well-known example of Akayu is the Kinsen ("Golden Spring") of {{ill|Arima Onsen|ja|有馬温泉}}.
The distinctive red color often influences the naming of hot springs as "Akayu." However, not all Akayu are red; for instance, the {{ill|Akayu Onsen (Yamagata)|ja|赤湯温泉 (山形県)}} in {{ill|Yamagata Prefecture|ja|山形県}} features clear, colorless water. This name was derived from local {{ill|Open Spring Legends|ja|開湯伝説}} rather than the water's appearance.
